Tropical Storms

The data for this notebook consists of information about tropical storms in the Atlantic Ocean between 1950 and 2020. It gives one row each time a particular storm is measured (usually every 6 hours). Note that you will need to use both the year and name of the storm to uniquely describe it. I will add the code here to convert the dataset to a spatial points data table.

storms <- read_csv("../data/storms2.csv") |>
  st_as_sf(coords = c("lon", "lat"), crs = 4326, remove = FALSE)

The variables are:

  • year the year of the record
  • month the month of the year
  • day the day of the year
  • hour the hour of the day (0-23) of the record in Eastern time
  • name a common name for the storm; these are sometimes used for different storms in different years
  • letter the first letter of the name; storms are (usually) named in alphabetical order
  • doy the day of the year (1-365) of the record
  • lat latitude of the record in degrees
  • lon longitude of the record in degrees
  • status a two-digit status code of the storm system; see “storm_codes.csv”
  • category for hurricanes (status == “HU”), a number giving the category of the storm from 0-5
  • wind the observed sustained wind speed in miles per hour

There are also two metadata tables. The first provides a full name for each of these codes:

storm_codes <- read_csv("../data/storm_codes.csv")

Question 1: Make datetime object [temporal]

Take the storms data and create a new column called time that is a date time object created by the year, month, day, and hour of the storm’s measurement. You will need this variable in the following questions, so overwrite the data storms with the new version that contains the time column.

# Question 01
storms <- storms |>
  mutate(time = make_datetime(year, month, day, hour))

Question 2: Plot datetime objects [temporal]

Take the storms data and take just the hurricanes (status code “HU”) from the year 2017. Group by the time variable you created in question 1 and count the number of readings for each unique time. Create a plot with the data in which the x-axis gives the time and the y-axis gives the number of hurricane readings in 2017 at that time. Set the date_breaks and date_minor_breaks to both be “1 week” and the date labels to be “%d %b”.

# Question 02
storms |>
  filter(year == 2017) |>
  filter(status == "HU") |>
  group_by(time) |>
  summarize(n = n()) |>
  ggplot(aes(time, n)) +
    geom_point() +
    scale_x_datetime(
      date_breaks = "1 week",
      date_minor_breaks = "1 week",
      date_labels = "%d %b"
    )

Question 3: Create and plot date data [temporal]

Filter the data to include only category 5 hurricanes. Group the data by year and hurricane name and compute the maximum wind speed of each storm. Create a plot that has year on x-axis and max-wind speed on the y-axis. Use both a points layer and a geom_text_repel with the name of the storm. Make sure that the x-axis is a date object and set date_breaks to be ‘5 year’ and the date labels to “%Y”.

# Question 03
storms |>
  filter(status == "HU") |>
  filter(category == 5) |>
  group_by(year, name) |>
  summarize(max_wind = max(wind)) |>
  mutate(year = make_date(year)) |>
  ggplot(aes(year, max_wind)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_text_repel(aes(label = name)) +
    scale_x_date(date_breaks = "5 year", date_labels = "%Y")

Question 4: Create and plot date data [temporal]

Take the storms data, using all records, and group by year and name. Summarize the data by taking the difference between the maximum and minimum times for readings of each storm. Ungroup the data and arrange in descending order, with the longes t lasting storms at the top. You should see one outlier at the top of the list resulting from a bad data point.

# Question 04
storms |>
  group_by(year, name) |>
  summarize(duration = max(time) - min(time)) |>
  ungroup() |>
  arrange(desc(duration))

Question 5: Spatial polygons [temporal]

Create a plot of the states in state_se in the coordinate system with CRS code 5069.

# Question 05
state_se |>
  st_transform(5069) |>
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf()

Question 6: Spatial points [spatial]

Select the storms data from the 2004 storm “Jeanne”. Create a spatial plot with the measurements of the storm’s wind speed overlaid over the state boundaries. Color the points based on the status code and use the 5069 coordinate system.

# Question 06
storms |>
  filter(year == 2004) |>
  filter(name == "Jeanne") |>
  st_transform(5069) |>
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(data = state_se) +
    geom_sf(aes(color = status))

Question 7: Spatial join [spatial]

Filter the storms data to include only hurricanes (status code “HU”). Perform a spatial join with the states data, group by the state names, and summarize to count the number of hurricane readings in each state. Sort from the state with the most readings to the state with the fewest. After the spatial join, use the as_tibble() function to remove the spatial information (this would be helpful if the dataset were larger). You should see a large set of NA’s corresponding to points that were out in the ocean.

Save this dataset as a table called storm_obs_per_state

# Question 07
storm_obs_per_state <- storms |>
  filter(status == "HU") |>
  spatial_join(state_se) |>
  as_tibble() |>
  group_by(state) |>
  summarize(n = n()) |>
  arrange(desc(n))

Question 8: Spatial join plot [spatial]

Below, create a plot of the Southeastern U.S. states, using the color of the states to show how many hurricane readings there were in each state in the dataset. Do this by doing an inner join of state_se with the dataset storm_obs_per_state you created in the previous question. Use the color scale:

scale_fill_distiller( palette = 8, guide = “legend”, n.breaks = 10, direction = 1 )

# Question 08
state_se |>
  inner_join(storm_obs_per_state, by = "state") |>
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(aes(fill = n), size = 0)  +
    scale_fill_distiller(
      palette = 8, guide = "legend", n.breaks = 10, direction = 1
    )

We could have done this with a single pipe without first creating the dataset in question 7 as an intermediate step. Why is the approach above preferred? The benefit is that it does not force us to create lots of copies of the (relatively large) spatial polygons that a single pipe would require. The data on the actual exam is large enough that not splitting this into two steps would be a problem for most of your machines.
